Learn more at http://docs.sensum.co/#sentiment-command

The Sensum Location Ios Sample Code demonstrates how to update, record, and send location data to the API. Location events are automatically timestamped when receiving actionable commands such as starting a workout or finished jogging.

The Sensum Bluetooth Ios Sample Code demonstrates how to connect to Bluetooth to measure a user's heart rate. Along with Bluetooth, developers can also use Mio Link, Mio Alpha 2, Scosche Rhythm+, and Shimmer2r GSR (for Android Only). To learn more, visit
http://help.sensum.co/knowledge_base/topics/what-type-of-sensors-can-i-use

The Sensum Receiving Values from API Android Sample Code demonstrates how to receive the value of the SensumAPI as if values from a device are received. To achieve the result, developers can set up the BroadcastReceiver in the MainActivity, then include the filters provided in table four. http://docs.sensum.co/#receiving-values-from-sensumapi

The Sensum Capturing Data Android Sample Code demonstrates how to capture data from the service to send it to the API. To achieve this result, developers can create a button object that implements the sendtoService method. That way, the button can start and stop the recording of data.
The Sensum Receiving GPS Android Sample Code demonstrates how to send acceleration values from the service to the frontend. Developers can include GPS and ACC filters to receive on broadcast method.

The Sensum Android Sample Code demonstrates how developers can use the Sensum Emotion Artificial Intelligence toolkit. Learning tools include managing project dependencies, implementing Shimmer library, using a broadcast receiver, Bluetooth, receiving GPS and acceleration values, realm queries, signing in with Google, and using Gradle dependencies.

The Microsoft Azure u-SQL .NET Sample Code by Saveen Reddy demonstrates how to create a cognitive application that extracts phrases from paragraphs. To achieve such result, developers can use key phrase array and sentiment analyzer. To learn more, visit https://github.com/Azure-Samples/usql-cognitive-text-hello-world

The Microsoft Azure PhotoMosaic .NET Sample Code by Dona Malayeri demonstrates how to create a photo mosaic from an input image by using Azure Functions and Custom Vision Service. To start the project, developers can generate API Keys, set up custom vision service project, configure the photo mosaic project, load tile images, and run the project.

The Microsoft Azure WebAPI OpenID Connect .NET Sample Code by Jean-Marc Prieur demonstrates how to create an MVC app that uses OpenID connect protocol, calls the Web API, and authenticates with tokens via OAuth 2.0.

The Microsoft Azure Xamarin Forms .NET Sample Code by Jean-Marc Prieur demonstrates how to use Xamarin forms by authenticating via MSAL library. https://github.com/AzureAD/microsoft-authentication-library-for-dotnet
To run the sample, developers need Visual Studio 2017, an Internet connection, and Azure AD B2C tenant.

The Microsoft Azure Core Data Lake .NET Sample Code demonstrates how to wrap an API with the Azure Data Lake SDK. To use the package, visit the demo site at https://github.com/Azure-Samples/data-lake-dotnet-client/tree/master/src

The Microsoft Azure Core Web API .NET Sample Code by Danny Strockis demonstrates how to build an API by using Azure AD B2C and the ASP.Net Core JWT Bearer middleware. The API includes CRUD operations with GET, PUT, POST, and DELETE verbs. To learn how to create an app without signing in and out, visit https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory-b2c/active-directory-b2c-overview

The Microsoft Azure Job Search .NET Sample Code by Liam Cavanagh demonstrates how to browse jobs available on the NYC Open Data. Jobs listed are not necessarily active, aiming to serve as a reference point for developers.

The Microsoft Azure Table Storage .NET Sample Code by Jason Hogg demonstrates how to use the Azure Cosmos DB Table API to create a table, CRUD operations, batch operations, and querying techniques. The aim is to create responsive applications while using asynchronous APIs, calling the storage service with the await keyword.

The Microsoft Azure Service Fabric .NET Sample Code by Mikkel Mork Hegnhoj demonstrates how to use service communication and reliable dictionaries. To learn more about Fabric, Microsoft's distributed system service platform, visit https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/service-fabric/service-fabric-quickstart-dotnet

The Microsoft Azure Government PaaS .NET Sample Code by Steve Michelotti demonstrates how to create a Core MVC web app that uses OpenID to sign in users. It aims to help with reading and writing the Azure SQL database, while using queues and redis cache.

The Microsoft Azure Intelligent Mission .NET Sample Code by Steve Michelotti demonstrates how organizations can use Cognitive Services in government scenarios. It includes face detection, face identification, object recognition in images, OCR in images, sentiment analysis, text translation, and speaker identification.
The TapResearch Simple Integration Android Sample Code is a test application that demonstrates the functionalities of TapResearch's survey/research platform.
This TapResearch Supply JavaScript Sample Code shows how to configure the SDK to track user sessions, and to supply reward surveys.

The Microsoft Azure Active Directory .NET Sample Code by Jean-Marc Prieur demonstrates how to create an MVC web application from an Azure Active Directory using OpenID Connect middleware. This and other samples are available on Microsoft with additional authentication scenarios. To learn more, visit
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/develop/active-directory-authentication-scenarios

The Microsoft Azure OpenID Connect .NET Sample Code by Danny Strockis demonstrates how to create an MVC web app by using OpenID as a method to sign-in users. To run the sample, developers can clone or download the repository, register the sample with Azure Active Tenant, configure the sample, and then run.

The Microsoft Azure Multitenant SaaS .NET Sample Code by Danny Strockis demonstrates how to build an MVC web app that uses OpenID connect to sign up. The steps to run the sample cover cloning or downloading the repository, registering the sample with an Azure Active Directory tenant, provisioning a key for the app in your Azure Active Directory tenant, and configuring the sample to use the Azure Active Directory tenant. Before running the sample, an optional step is creating an Azure Active Directory test tenant.

The Microsoft Azure Develop with Cassandra API .NET Sample Code by Mohit Jindal demonstrates how to create an Azure Cosmos DB account for the Cassandra API, an Apache database that aims to support the replication of multiple datacenters. By experimenting with the code, developers will build a user profile console app and output with sample data.

The Microsoft Azure Run Console Apps .NET Sample Code by muralivp demonstrates how to run the console apps by using .exe as a web service. Developers can specify input parameters, use binary files, and specify download URL. The aim with this and other Azure samples is to create compute on-demand apps. To learn more, visit https://github.com/Azure-Samples/functions-dotnet-migrating-console-apps

The Microsoft Azure Core Web API .NET Sample Code by Jean-Marc Prieur demonstrates developers how to use the API. To run the sample, they can install .NET core for Windows adding Visual Studio, ensure they have an Azure Active Directory, and a user account in the Azure AD tenant.

The Microsoft Azure Data Catalog .NET Sample Code by Sreedhar Pelluru demonstrates how to register, search, and delete a data asset using the Data Catalog REST API, when using the Service Principal authentication. GitHub code available at https://github.com/Azure-Samples/data-catalog-dotnet-service-principal-get-started

The Microsoft Azure Services PlayReady .NET Sample Code by Julia Kornich demonstrates how to ingest, encode, protect, and stream content. It allows encrypting with PlayReady and Widevide licenses. To run the sample, developers need Visual Studio, an Azure subscription, and the latest .NET SDK.

The Microsoft Azure Encrypt Assets AES-128 .NET Sample Code by Julia Kornich demonstrates how to encrypt content with the keys AES 128-bit. By using Visual Studio and a subscription, developers can clone or download the repository, update the app.config file, start a streaming point, and run the sample.

The Microsoft Azure Using PlayReady and Common Encryption .NET Sample Code by Julia Kornich demonstrates how to encrypt content with PlayReady, a media file copy prevention technology from Microsoft. In this sample, developers can learn how to run the sample in Visual Studio previously subscribing to Azure.

The Microsoft Azure Encrypt Apple FairPlay .NET Sample Code by Julia Kornich demonstrates how to encrypt an HTTP live streaming content by using Apple FairPlay. Developers will find that individual audio and video samples are encrypted in AES-128 CBC mode. In addition to encryption, they can specify the type of licenses that will be delivered to the clients. Currently, the project natively supports iOS and AppleTV, while Safari OS enables FPS using EME interface.

The Microsoft Azure Encode and Deliver a Live Stream .NET Sample Code by Julia Kornich presents developers how to build a channel to receive a live stream and encode it to multi-bitrate stream. To run the sample, developers can use Nuget to install the SDK, followed by installing the Windows Azure package, and update the appSettings section.

The Microsoft Azure Copy Blobs .NET Sample Code by Julia Kornich demonstrates how to copy blobs from a storage account into a new Azure Media Services asset. With the sample, developers can use AMS accounts to organize assets, storage accounts, and use an authentication method.
The Bing Search .NET Sample Code demonstrates how to interact with the API to send a search query to Bing and get back search results that include links to web pages, images, and rankings.

The Vize Start Training Python Sample Code demonstrates how to start training the artificial intelligence application with the URL https://api.vize.ai/v1/training/start/, the authorization API token, and the task ID data. Successful responses will show model training, depending on the number of images in training dataset.

The Vize Training Image Python Sample Code demonstrates how to train images to be recognized by machine learning. To receive a response, developers first access the URL https://api.vize.ai/v1/training-image/, authorize via token, and open the path file. Both successful and error responses are possible with if and else statements.

The Vize Label Python Sample Code demonstrates how to access label features for image recognition apps, when developers visit the URL https://api.vize.ai/v1/label/
They can authorize via token to use the task ID for receiving responses to their requests.

The Vize Task Python Sample Code presents how to access tasks in image recognition applications. Developers can import requests when they access the URL https://api.vize.ai/v1/task/, authorize with a token, and use the appropriate headers as requests.

The Vize Image Recognition Ruby Sample Code demonstrates how to recognize images when developers use the address http://unirest.io/ruby open-source library. After authorizing with a token, they can accept text or plain content type in return to the image request.

The Vize Image Recognition .NET Sample Code demonstrates how to recognize images by using the HTTP
http://unirest.io/net open-source library.
Developers can accept images in return when they authorize with token and request content type.

The Vize Image Recognition Objective-C Sample Code presents how to recognize images by initially requesting to the HTTP address http://unirest.io/objective-c
Developers can authorize with token, set the URL to classify images, and have the images recognized in return with their respective header response.

The Vize Image Recognition Java Sample Code presents how to recognize an image when developers access the HTTP address http://unirest.io/java open-source library
They can have data in return when they authorize with token, request content type, and accept text or plain result.

The Vize Image Recognition Node.js Sample Code presents how to recognize an image when developers use the HTTP http://unirest.io/nodejs open-source library
They will install npm and unirest followed by authorizing with token, request and accept content type and attach image and task.

The Vize Image Recognition PHP Sample Code presents how to recognize an image by handling the cURL https://api.vize.ai/v1/classify/
Developers can access data in return when they request post fields, return transfer, and HTTP header.

The Vize Image Recognition Python Sample Code demonstrates how to identify an image by accessing the URL https://api.vize.ai/v1/classify/
Developers can authorize with API token, access image file, and find data task ID.

The Microsoft Azure LUIS Transfer Objects .NET Sample Code by George Wallace presents how to get started with Azure and implement transfer objects into language and other Azure applications. The Azure Storage documentation is available at https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/
LUIS stands for Language Understanding Intelligent Service.

The Microsoft Azure LUIS Circuit Breaker Pattern .NET Sample Code by Robin Shahan demonstrates how while using language understanding features, developers can use the Circuit Breaker pattern with an RA-GRS storage account. To learn more about how to develop apps, learn at https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/
LUIS stands for Language Understanding Intelligent Service.

The Microsoft Azure LUIS Storage Performance .NET Sample Code by George Wallace demonstrates how to create a virtual machine with random files that are uploaded and downloaded to a storage account. The aim is to showcase scalability and performance when using the Azure storage SDK, while implementing intelligent services with language understanding.
LUIS stands for Language Understanding Intelligent Service.

The Microsoft Azure LUIS Media .NET Sample Code by John Deutscher demonstrates how to ingest content from blob storage, encode, write content back to blob storage, monitor job notifications via WebHooks and Azure Queues. Developers have the option to edit the code with Visual Studio, along with Azure Functions CLI.
LUIS stands for Language Understanding Intelligent Service.

The Microsoft Azure LUIS Fabric .NET Sample Code by Vaclav Turecek presents how to work with Microsoft Azure Service Fabric, to build and operate scalable and distributed apps. Service fabric aims to build applications that are logic, reliable, scalable, manageable, and latent. As an official infrastructure as a service for building apps, Microsoft also includes other services for integration, such as Skype for Business, Intune, Azure Event Hubs, Azure Data Factory, Azure Cosmos DB, Azure SQL Database, Dynamics 365, and Cortana.
https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/services/service-fabric/
LUIS stands for Language Understanding Intelligent Service.

The Microsoft Azure LUIS Programmatic .NET Sample Code by Carol Hanna presents how to use the SDK to create and customize new LUIS apps. Developers will work with a Bot Framework that allows a chatbot to talk with a user via text input and the Bing Speech API that converts spoken language requests into text. Once converted to text, LUIS processes the requests.
Additional samples by the author are available at https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/resources/samples/cognitive-services-luis-console-application/
LUIS stands for Language Understanding Intelligent Service.

The Microsoft Azure LUIS Console .NET Sample Code by Carol Hanna guides developers to consume the LUIS Runtime SDK to predict user utterances. With the LUIS app, they can put together the intents and entities that are important to a particular task.
To create a sample LUIS app, visit https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cognitive-services/luis/
